Aims¶

Initially, the aim of this notebook was to analyze our RSVP data and see which schools I have to encourage to send more e-mails to their listservs. This RSVP data was collected until the night before the conference which was held on the 23rd of April, 2019. Now post-conference, we are also interested in our check-in rates. We are using pandas for data wrangling and altair for plotting.

RSVP Data¶

Let's first load up our RSVP data:

In [2]:
df = pd.read_csv('rsvp_data.csv')
df['time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['time'])
print(f'We are analyzing {df.shape[0]} RSVPs!')
df.head()

We are analyzing 779 RSVPs!

rsvp_no time institution status

1 2 2019-03-14 19:11:00 Other Attending
2 3 2019-03-18 14:28:00 Non-academic Institution Attending
3 4 2019-03-19 16:33:00 CUNY Checked In
4 5 2019-03-19 16:45:00 CUNY Checked In

I cleaned this data set beforehand, by removing duplicates (only about 10 or so people signed up twice with different e-mails - always kept the earlier RSVP) and removing any personal data, i.e. e-mails, company, etc. that could be used to identify our attendees/ compromise their privacy.

The data set, where each row represents a person who signed up, contains the following columns:

  • rsvp_no: Was the person who signed up the 1st, the 2nd, 3rd or nth?
  • time: When did the person sign up?
  • institution: Were they from a Non-academic institution, from one of the New York City Schools that we listed or other?
  • status: Did they just sign up "Attending" or did they also end up showing up at the conference and were checked in by us "Checked In"? We checked in everyone that entered the conference hall, as required by Columbia University (CU) rules. A CU security professional made sure nobody entered without being checked in.

The status data analysis is at the bottom of this notebook.

We used this information around April 11th to motivate additional advertising efforts by Columbia and other schools. What we had noticed was that after weeks of advertising, one clickbaity e-mail at NYU still brought in a huge upwards spike in RSVPs (around 10th of April), meaning that the common fear of over-exposing a target audience to ads would diminish their willingness to RSVP for the conference.

We can tell that NYU was bringing the most RSVPs on April 11th, but we the colleagues at Columbia were able to close the gap. One also has to consider that CUNY was split up into different labels late in the process. If one were to add the CUNY RSVPs up towards the end, they would fall between Weill Cornell and Einstein. Additionally we see quite a few RSVPs for Non-academic Institution, emphasizing that at our conference you don't just have the panelists and speakers to network with, but also your fellow attendees from industry.

When were the biggest spikes in signups/ e-mail blasts¶

The aim here is to have some fun with the numbers to estimate when each university received e-mail blasts, by looking at the differential in signups over time.

We will make use of the following solution, which attempts to compute the local gradient from incoherently sampled data:

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/41780489/python-pandas-how-to-calculate-derivative-gradient

It would probably be a lot easier to read if we used a windowed count of RSVPs. So let's try counting the number of RSVPs in a 2h window:

In [9]:
rsvp_2h_avg_institution = df.groupby('institution').apply(             # we group by institution
    lambda frame: frame.set_index('time').counts.rolling('2H').count() # for every institution, we want to do a rolling average of unique RSVPs with a 2h time window
).reset_index(                                                         # resetting the index, so it's easier to consume for altair
)
rsvp_2h_avg_institution.groupby('institution').head().head(10)         # showing that the counts make sense - if time points are 2h apart, then they are counted together

We can pretty clearly see that there is a burst of peaks from Columbia in the last two weeks and if you look clearly, there was another burst right around March 25th, which is when we all started advertising. NYU, only has a couple of peaks but major activity at each of those peaks. This could be tied to a larger audience (the PhD program at NYU is one of the larger ones in the country), stronger receptiveness for career development opportunities, or more effective marketing.

You may also ask why we have RSVPs from before then and that's because some of our members already RSVPed for the conference when the website was not public yet.

TRI-I (Weill Cornell, Rockefeller and Memorial Sloan Kettering) show reduced number of RSVP peaks, which is mostly because of multiple other career events that happened in the marketing period and would have clashed with advertising for the local events, plus the organizers of those events were of course busy with organizing their own events.

What time of the day do people sign up?¶

Conventional wisdom has it that people mostly respond to e-mails in the morning but what time of day do people sign up the most?

We do have to take into account here that our results are going to be biased around when we sent e-mails but it might still be interesting to look at.

In [12]:
hourly_rsvps_institution = df.groupby(['institution', df.time.dt.hour]).size().reset_index().rename(columns={0:'counts'})
hourly_rsvps_institution.head()
Out[12]:
institution time counts
0 CUNY 7 1
1 CUNY 9 8
2 CUNY 10 1
3 CUNY 11 1
4 CUNY 12 5

Out[13]:
In [14]:
alt.Chart(hourly_rsvps_institution).properties(width=600)\
.mark_area()\
.encode(
    x='time',
    y=alt.Y('counts', stack='zero'),
    color=alt.Color('institution',
        scale=alt.Scale(scheme='category20')),
    tooltip='institution'
).interactive()
Out[14]:

This shows that we got most of our RSVPs around 10 am. It is however important to keep in mind that:

a) RSVPs are usually do not necessarily have to be following an e-mail instantly, i.e. getting most RSVPs at 10 am means the best time to e-mail could be before then.

b) We tried to e-mail around 9 am, so our data collection is fundamentally biased.

There is a second hump in the afternoon, because we would often send out an e-mail after lunch if we did not get to it before lunch. Some of the RSVPs during the nightly hours are likely by folks on conferences abroad or otherwise. What is somewhat surprising is the steady amouind of RSVPs from 8 pm to midnight - many folks checking their e-mails late at night.

Any of these hypothesis would need to be tested with varying e-mail timing randomly across a cohort.

Even then it would be difficult to assess because if we randomly subselect for example NYU students, some of the recipients of the earlier e-mails could talk to their colleagues who receive later e-mails, enhancing the effectiveness of later e-mails.

Summary¶

We have learned

  • we can use RSVP data to analyse the response of our different communities
  • repeated e-mails do not substantially lower the effectiveness of advertising (we don't generally e-mail more than once per day)
  • repeated e-mail blasts over short periods of time may be highly effective (Columbia, 2 weeks before conference)
  • peak response is at 10 am but likely due to when we usually send our e-mails

Check-in Data (post conference)¶

Getting RSVPs is nice and well, but when push comes to shove and the conference is actually happening, we are interested in how many RSVPs turn into people showing up at our conference.

In [15]:
checkin_summary = pd.concat((100* df.status.value_counts()/ df.shape[0], df.status.value_counts()), axis=1)
checkin_summary.columns = ["% of total RSVPs","Number of RSVPs"]
checkin_summary
Out[15]:
% of total RSVPs Number of RSVPs
Attending 58.793325 458
Checked In 41.206675 321

We recorded a 41% check-in rate! That's very good for a free event like ours and about what we usually record. All in all, we were able to attract 321 attendees - together with our panelists and speakers, that makes about 350 people!

Let's now take a look at which universities had the best conversion rates:

In [16]:
check_in_perc_by_institution = df.groupby('institution')\
.apply(lambda group: group.status.value_counts()/group.shape[0])\
.reset_index()\
.rename(columns={'level_1':'status', 'status':'percentage of institution RSVPs'})
alt.vconcat(
alt.Chart(check_in_perc_by_institution)\
.mark_bar()\
.encode(
    x='institution',
    y='percentage of institution RSVPs',
    color='status'
),
alt.Chart(
    df.institution.value_counts()\
    .reset_index().rename(columns={'index':'institution', 'institution':'number of total RSVPS'})
         ).mark_bar().encode(
    x='institution',
    y='number of total RSVPS'
))
Out[16]:

We can see there are a couple of outliers with either 100% show-rate or 0%, which can be attributed to low numbers of RSVPs (4 or less) from those institutions. Einstein, closely followed by Mount Sinai, has the highest show-rate from any of the institutions with more than just a few attendees.

However, the difference in show-rate between the universities is relatively miniscule, emphasizing the importance of advertizing, as in the case of a pretty stable show-rate, the amount of people showing up from each university depends on how many of them RSVP. In the previous paragraph, we established that our data supports that continued advertising results in more RSVPs.

In short: we find on evidence for the hypothesis that continued advertising results in some sort of fatigue that decreases the amount of RSVPs or the conversion rate from RSVPs to showing up.

Next we might be interested in if there is any bias in terms of time when it comes to how likely our RSVPs are to show up:

Let's see if there is a time-bias for the signups at any of the institutions:

In [19]:
# using seaborn here because altair, or rather its backend vega-lite will put the attending and
# checked in boxplots ontop of each other for each university, instead of next to each other
p = sns.boxplot(data=df_week, x='institution', y='week', hue='status')
p.set_xticklabels(p.get_xmajorticklabels(), rotation=90)
p
Out[19]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f3cbdc6ae48>

Looks like there is some time bias for the Non-academic Institution RSVPs, which represent people from industry. We can see that the industry RSVPs that did not show up, all signed up very early in advance. However, from those industry RSVPs that did show up, we see representation over the entire timeline of us advertizing, so no reason to only advertize towards industry close to the conference.

Columbia also has the reverse scenario, where RSVPs that showed up to the conference tended to fall closer to the conference, while no-shows were represented throughout the entire time of advertizing. This can however be attributed more to the increased late advertizing at Columbia.

Summary¶

we have learned:

  • About 40% of our RSVPs show up at the conference, consistent with previous events
  • Among the universities that were represented by more than 10 people, there was some fluctuation but overall similar rates between institutions
  • Einstein and Mount Sinai had exceptional slightly higher, NYU and Columbia slightly lower rates
  • Overall, there is little to no influence of the time someone RSVPed onto how likely they also show up
  • There are some trends in terms of the influence of time on RSVP when viewed by institution, which can be explained by advertizing patterns
